# Copy this file to .env and fill in real values:  cp .env.example .env
# .env is gitignored — your real values never get committed.

# --- Server / system ---
SERVER_NAME=home-server
RAID_MOUNT=/mnt/storage
# OS/root filesystem reported on the System widget. Default "/" is the container's
# own root (an overlay backed by the host OS disk), so it matches the host with no
# extra mount — only override if the container root lives on a different device.
SYSTEM_DISK_MOUNT=/
# Path to YOUR server's markdown guide, shown on the in-app "Server Guide" page.
# Leave unset to show the committed example template; point it at your own
# (gitignored, host-specific) doc to show that instead.
# SERVER_GUIDE_FILE=/home/you/docs/SERVER_GUIDE.md
# Path to YOUR home catalog (YAML), shown on the "Home Catalog" page — a
# floor-by-floor inventory of devices, appliances, tools, and infrastructure.
# Leave unset to show the committed generic example; point it at your own
# (gitignored, host-specific) catalog to show that instead. Also read by the HA
# collector (scripts/ha-state.py) to overlay LIVE device state onto catalog
# items wired to a Home Assistant entity (needs HA_URL/HA_TOKEN configured too).
# CATALOG_FILE=/home/you/docs/home-catalog.yaml

# --- Plex ---
PLEX_URL=http://localhost:32400
PLEX_TOKEN=your-token-here

# --- Library (your owned games + reading content, played/read in-app) — optional ---
# Folder of game ROMs the Library's Games section lists + streams. Keep it under
# RAID_MOUNT so it's served by the existing read-only RAID mount (no extra mount).
# Phase 1 recognizes Game Boy/Color (.gb/.gbc) and GBA (.gba). Unset = the Games
# section reports "not configured" and the hub hides it. ROMs are yours to supply.
# Also install the emulator engine once: scripts/fetch-emulatorjs.sh
# GAMES_ROM_DIR=/mnt/storage/roms
# Folder of PDFs for the Library's Magazines & Papers section (read in-browser
# via PDF.js). Under RAID_MOUNT, same as above. Unset = the section is hidden.
# PAPERS_DIR=/mnt/storage/magazines-papers
# Folder of ebooks for the Library's Books section — EPUB/MOBI/AZW3 (and PDFs),
# read in-browser via foliate-js (no server-side conversion). Under RAID_MOUNT.
# Unset = the section is hidden. DRM-free files only (Kindle DRM won't open).
# BOOKS_DIR=/mnt/storage/ebooks
# Folder of comics for the Library's Comics section — CBZ/CBR/CB7 (zip/rar/7z
# archives of page images), read page-by-page in-browser. Under RAID_MOUNT.
# Unset = the section is hidden.
# COMICS_DIR=/mnt/storage/comics
# Folder of audiobooks for the Library's Audiobooks section — each book is a
# subfolder of ordered audio files (mp3/m4a/m4b/…), played in-browser. Under
# RAID_MOUNT. Unset = the section is hidden. (Audible DRM .aa/.aax won't play.)
# AUDIOBOOKS_DIR=/mnt/storage/audiobooks
# Books search index (a background worker parses each book's title/author into a
# small text-only cache so Books is searchable). On by default; tune if needed:
# BOOKS_INDEX_ENABLED=true
# BOOKS_INDEX_INTERVAL=3600   # seconds between re-scans for new/changed files
# Save states are stored here (defaults to the backend data volume, which lives
# under the host's / so they roam across devices AND ride the off-site backup):
# GAMES_SAVES_DIR=/data/saves
# (Reading sections — comics/books/papers — get their own dirs as they're added.)

# --- Backend ---
API_PORT=8000
# Path to the Docker socket on the host (mounted read-only into the backend)
DOCKER_SOCKET=/var/run/docker.sock
# Container log viewer: comma-separated container names whose logs the
# /api/containers/{name}/logs endpoint refuses to return. Logs are raw
# stdout/stderr and can contain secrets/activity an app prints, so list the
# sensitive ones (e.g. a VPN gateway or a download client). Empty = all logs readable
# (only ever over the LAN/tailnet — never the public internet).
# CONTAINER_LOGS_EXCLUDE=gluetun,downloader

# --- Config backup (age) ---
# Public ("recipient") key the backup script encrypts to. Generate a keypair on
# your OWN machine (age-keygen); put the PUBLIC key here, keep the private key in
# a password manager. The server can encrypt but never decrypt.
AGE_RECIPIENT=age1yourpublickeyhere
# Directory (on persistent storage) where encrypted backups are written.
# Keep it under RAID_MOUNT so the UI can list it via the existing mount.
BACKUP_DIR=/mnt/storage/backups/home-hq
# How many backups to keep before pruning the oldest.
BACKUP_RETENTION=14

# --- External-drive watchdog (optional) ---
# Only needed if you have a flaky USB drive whose bridge periodically "wedges"
# (I/O hangs while the device stays connected). The host watchdog service
# (scripts/drive-watchdog.sh) probes the mount and auto-recovers. Leave unset to
# disable. MOUNT must have an /etc/fstab entry (that's where mount options live).
# WATCHDOG_MOUNT=/mnt/external          # mount point to watch
# WATCHDOG_UUID=XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX        # filesystem UUID (blkid) of the partition
# WATCHDOG_USB_ID=0bda:9210             # USB vendor:product of the bridge; set to
#                                       # enable the software reset (lsusb)
# WATCHDOG_LABEL=external-drive         # display label for logs / the state file
# WATCHDOG_FSTYPE=ntfs                  # optional; auto-detected from the device
# WATCHDOG_REPAIR_CMD=                  # optional override for the fsck step
# WATCHDOG_STATE_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/drive-watchdog.json
# WATCHDOG_EVENTS_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/drive-watchdog-events.jsonl  # recovery log
# Tuning (seconds / counts), shown with their defaults:
# WATCHDOG_CHECK_INTERVAL=30
# WATCHDOG_PROBE_TIMEOUT=20
# WATCHDOG_FAIL_THRESHOLD=2
# WATCHDOG_COOLDOWN=60
# WATCHDOG_BACKOFF=300

# --- VPN egress health (optional) ---
# If you route a container's traffic through a VPN, a host timer
# (scripts/vpn-health.py) compares the container's public egress IP against the
# host's own and writes vpn.json; the backend serves /api/vpn and the VPN page
# shows it + alerts on a leak. Defaults shown; the backend reads VPN_JSON via the
# same /smart mount as SMART. Install scripts/home-hq-vpn-health.{service,timer}.
# VPN_CONTAINER=gluetun                  # container whose egress to check
# VPN_IP_CHECK_URL=https://ipinfo.io/json   # primary lookup (gives geo + org)
# Plain-text IP echoes used when the JSON service fails — popular shared VPN exit
# IPs get rate-limited (HTTP 429) by ipinfo's free tier, which would otherwise
# read as a false "VPN down". These give just the IP (no geo), which is all the
# leak check needs.
# VPN_IP_FALLBACK_URLS=https://api.ipify.org,https://ifconfig.me/ip,https://icanhazip.com
# VPN_FORWARDED_PORT_FILE=/tmp/gluetun/forwarded_port   # in-container path
# VPN_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/vpn.json     # host output path (read at /smart/vpn.json)

# --- Tailscale mesh status (optional) ---
# If this host is on a Tailscale tailnet, a host timer (scripts/tailscale-
# status.py) runs `tailscale status --json` and writes tailscale.json; the
# backend serves /api/tailscale and the Tailscale page lists every device with
# its online state and exit-node role. The backend reads TAILSCALE_JSON via the
# same /smart mount as SMART. Install scripts/home-hq-tailscale.{service,timer}.
# TAILSCALE_BIN=tailscale                       # path to the tailscale CLI
# TAILSCALE_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/tailscale.json  # host output (read at /smart/tailscale.json)

# --- Home Assistant glance (optional, read-only) ---
# Surface a curated handful of HA entities on the dashboard's "Home" widget,
# each row deep-linking into HA for control. HQ is the infra cockpit; HA is the
# smart-home brain — this is NOT a second smart-home UI, just a glance + handoff.
# A host timer (scripts/ha-state.py) calls HA's REST /api/states with a
# Long-Lived Access Token (generate one on your HA profile page), trims to the
# allowlist, and writes ha.json; the backend reads HA_JSON via the same /smart
# mount and serves /api/ha. Install scripts/home-hq-ha.{service,timer}. The token
# is a secret — it lives ONLY here, never in the repo or the container.
# HA_URL=http://localhost:8123
# HA_TOKEN=                          # Long-Lived Access Token (keep secret)
# Comma-separated entity ids, in display order. Each may be 'entity_id' or
# 'entity_id|Custom label' — the label overrides HA's friendly name in the glance
# (handy when an integration's names are long, e.g. "GE Washer … Machine State").
# HA_ENTITIES=sensor.dryer_machine_state|Dryer,sensor.dryer_time_remaining|Dryer time left
# HA_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/ha.json   # host output (read at /smart/ha.json)

# --- Plex activity history (in-app sampler → SQLite, powers the Plex insights page) ---
# Records concurrent streams / transcodes / bandwidth while Plex is reachable.
# PLEX_HISTORY_INTERVAL=300   # seconds between samples
# PLEX_HISTORY_DAYS=30        # retention window

# --- Speedtest / ISP monitor (in-app sampler runs the Ookla speedtest CLI) ---
# The backend can run the Ookla `speedtest` binary (baked into the image) on a
# schedule, store each result, and serve the trend at /api/speedtest.
# !! DATA COST: each gigabit test moves ~3.5 GB. A 6h interval = 4 tests/day ≈
# 14 GB/day — mind a metered/capped connection. Because of that cost the
# scheduler is OFF by default; opt in with SPEEDTEST_ENABLED=true. The in-app
# "Run test" button works either way.
# SPEEDTEST_ENABLED=true      # opt in to scheduled background tests (default off)
# SPEEDTEST_INTERVAL=21600    # seconds between scheduled tests (INTERVAL=0 = manual only)
# SPEEDTEST_RETENTION_DAYS=90 # how long to keep stored results
# SPEEDTEST_MIN_DOWNLOAD=0    # Mbps; >0 → alert when the latest download is below it (0 = no alert)

# --- What's-eating-space (cached daily `du` of RAID_MOUNT) — optional ---
# A background thread runs a niced top-level du once a day and caches the result.
# Disable if you'd rather not have the periodic scan.
# SPACE_SCAN_ENABLED=true
# SPACE_SCAN_INTERVAL=3600    # how often the thread checks whether a scan is due
# SPACE_SCAN_TIMEOUT=900      # max seconds a single du may run

# --- 3D printer (Bambu Lab) — all optional ---
# Leave these unset to disable the Printer module (it reports "not configured").
# No need for "LAN Only Mode" (that severs the cloud) — the local MQTT broker is
# reachable on your LAN while the printer stays cloud-connected. Just read these
# off the printer screen:
PRINTER_HOST=               # LAN IP — Settings > Network, e.g. 192.168.1.50
PRINTER_ACCESS_CODE=        # Access Code — Settings > Network (secret; keep it only here)
PRINTER_SERIAL=             # device serial — Settings > Device (used in the MQTT topic)
PRINTER_NAME=3D Printer     # display label in the UI
# PRINTER_MQTT_PORT=8883    # Bambu LAN MQTT is TLS on 8883 (rarely changed)
# Chamber camera (a separate TLS stream on :6000). Opt-in, since it may need its
# own network reachability (e.g. an extra port-forward to the printer's :6000):
# PRINTER_CAMERA=true
# PRINTER_CAMERA_PORT=6000
# Seconds to keep the camera connected after the last viewer leaves, then it
# disconnects to free the camera for Bambu Studio. The live MJPEG view re-asserts
# interest as it plays, so this only fires once nobody is watching.
# PRINTER_CAMERA_IDLE_TIMEOUT=10

# --- Solar (Enphase Envoy / IQ Gateway) — all optional ---
# Leave these unset to disable the Solar module (it reports "not configured").
# The backend reads the Envoy's LOCAL API via pyenphase; on firmware 7+ it mints
# a token from the Enlighten cloud using your homeowner login + the gateway's
# serial (read automatically), then auto-refreshes it (~6-month lifetime).
ENVOY_HOST=                 # Envoy's reachable host/IP (if it's behind a router NAT, the forward's WAN IP)
ENPHASE_USERNAME=           # Enlighten (enphaseenergy.com) homeowner login
ENPHASE_PASSWORD=           # Enlighten password (secret; keep it only here)
# ENPHASE_TOKEN=            # optional: a pre-minted token used instead of user/pass
# SOLAR_CACHE_TTL=10        # seconds to reuse the last Envoy poll (smooths widget polling)

# --- Weather (Open-Meteo) — all optional, FREE, NO API key ---
# Leave lat/lon unset to disable the Weather module (it reports "not configured").
# The backend hits Open-Meteo's free public forecast API directly — no key, no
# account — for current conditions + a 5-day forecast.
WEATHER_LAT=                # location latitude,  e.g. 40.71
WEATHER_LON=                # location longitude, e.g. -74.01
# WEATHER_UNITS=us          # us (°F / mph / inch) | metric (°C / km/h / mm)
# WEATHER_CACHE_TTL=600     # seconds to reuse the last poll (the fetch is slow; weather changes slowly)

# --- Alerting (push notifications via ntfy) — optional ---
# Get instant phone alerts (drive failing, backup failed, print done, etc).
# Push reaches your phone over normal internet — no Tailscale needed. Setup:
# install the ntfy app, pick an UNGUESSABLE topic (it's a shared secret),
# subscribe to it in the app, and set it here.
# ALERTS_ENABLED=true
# NTFY_URL=https://ntfy.sh
# NTFY_TOPIC=homehq-change-me-to-something-random
# NTFY_TOKEN=                  # only for self-hosted / reserved (auth) topics
# ALERT_CLICK_URL=             # optional: app base URL (e.g. https://host.example);
#                              # tapping an alert deep-links to its page (RAID -> /storage, etc.)
# ALERT_INTERVAL=120           # seconds between checks
# ALERT_DISK_PERCENT=95        # warn when a filesystem is this full
# ALERT_BACKUP_MAX_AGE_DAYS=8  # warn if no fresh backup in this many days
# ALERT_DB_MAX_MB=200          # warn if the local SQLite DB grows past this size
# Dead-man's switch: the engine pings this URL each cycle. Point it at an
# external check (e.g. a free Healthchecks.io check) that alerts YOU if the pings
# stop — so you find out when the box/backend/internet goes dark (the one failure
# your own alerting can't report on itself).
# HEALTHCHECK_PING_URL=https://hc-ping.com/your-uuid-here

# --- Uptime monitoring (optional) ---
# A host script (scripts/uptime-probe.py, run by a systemd timer) probes each
# service and writes uptime.json; the backend serves /api/uptime and the Uptime
# page shows status + uptime % + latency. It runs on the HOST (not the container)
# so it can reach LAN-restricted services the firewalled backend can't — probe
# via localhost where the service binds it. Targets are "Label|target" entries:
# target is an http(s):// URL (up = any response, even 401) or host:port (TCP).
# Read by the systemd unit (see scripts/home-hq-uptime.{service,timer}.example).
# UPTIME_TARGETS=Plex|http://localhost:32400,Home Assistant|http://localhost:8123
# UPTIME_INTERVAL=120   # probe cadence (keep in step with the timer)
# UPTIME_TIMEOUT=5      # per-probe timeout (seconds)
# UPTIME_JSON=/var/lib/home-hq/uptime.json   # host output (read at /smart/uptime.json)

# --- Frontend ---
VITE_API_BASE=/api
